  <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-1-2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        The Ideal Gas Law, <m>PV = RT</m>, relates the pressure (<m>P</m>, in pascals), temperature (<m>T</m>, in Kelvin), and volume (<m>V</m>, in cubic meters) of 1 mole of a gas (<m>R =  8.314 \ \frac{\text{J} }{\text{ mol }  \ \text{K} }</m> is the universal gas constant), and describes the behavior of gases that do not liquefy easily, such as oxygen and hydrogen. We can solve the ideal gas law for the volume and hence treat the volume as a function of the pressure and temperature:
        <md>
          V(P,T) = \frac{8.314T}{P}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain in detail what the trace of <m>V</m> with <m>P=1000</m> tells us about a key relationship between two quantities.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>V(1000,T) = \frac{8.314T}{1000}</m> represents the volume of 1 mole of a gas at a temp T, kelvin, when the pressure is 1000 pascals. This is a linear function with a positive slope of <m>\frac{8.314}{1000}</m>. As the temperature increases, the volume increases at a constant rate of <m>\frac{8.314 \frac{J}{mol k}}{1000 pascals}</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>V(1000,T) = \frac{8.314T}{1000}</m> represents the volume of 1 mole of a gas at a temp T, kelvin, when the pressure is 1000 pascals. This is a linear function with a positive slope of <m>\frac{8.314}{1000}</m>. As the temperature increases, the volume increases at a constant rate of <m>\frac{8.314 \frac{J}{mol k}}{1000 pascals}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain in detail what the trace of <m>V</m> with <m>T=5</m> tells us.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>V(P,5) = \frac{8.314(5)}{P}</m> represents the volume of 1 mole of a gas with a pressure of P, pascals, when the temperature is 5 Kelvin. This is a rational function. As the pressure increases, the volume decreases and approaches zero.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>V(P,5) = \frac{8.314(5)}{P}</m> represents the volume of 1 mole of a gas with a pressure of P, pascals, when the temperature is 5 Kelvin. This is a rational function. As the pressure increases, the volume decreases and approaches zero.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Explain in detail what the level curve <m>V = 0.5</m> tells us.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>V(P,T) = 0.5</m> represents the combinations of temperature and pressure that result in a volume of 1 mole of gas of 0.5 <m>m^{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>V(P,T) = 0.5</m> represents the combinations of temperature and pressure that result in a volume of 1 mole of gas of 0.5 <m>m^{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use 2 or three additional traces in each direction to make a rough sketch of the surface over the domain of <m>V</m> where <m>P</m> and <m>T</m> are each nonnegative.  Write at least one sentence that describes the way the surface looks.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>V(500,T), V(1000,T), and V(2000,T)</m> are traces that are linear functions with a positive slope.
            </p>
            <p>
              <m>V(P,5), V(P,10), and V(P,20)</m> are traces that are positive rational functions for <m>P \geq 0</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              These traces indicate the graph of <m>V</m> looks like a sheet of paper angling up through the <m>P</m> axis in the first octant that bends up towards the <m>VP</m>-plane.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>V(500,T), V(1000,T), and V(2000,T)</m> are traces that are linear functions with a positive slope.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>V(P,5), V(P,10), and V(P,20)</m> are traces that are positive rational functions for <m>P \geq 0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          These traces indicate the graph of <m>V</m> looks like a sheet of paper angling up through the <m>P</m> axis in the first octant that bends up towards the <m>VP</m>-plane.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Based on all your work above, write a couple of sentences that describe the effects that temperature and pressure have on volume.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The volume is directly proportional to the temperature and inversely proportional to the pressure. As temperature increases, the volume increases. As pressure increases, the volume decreases.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The volume is directly proportional to the temperature and inversely proportional to the pressure. As temperature increases, the volume increases. As pressure increases, the volume decreases.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="Ex-9-1-loans">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        When people buy a large ticket item like a car or a house, they often take out a loan to make the purchase. The loan is paid back in monthly installments until the entire amount of the loan, plus interest, is paid. The monthly payment that the borrower has to make depends on the amount <m>P</m> of money borrowed (called the principal), the duration <m>t</m> of the loan in years, and the interest rate <m>r</m>. For example, if we borrow $18,000 to buy a car, the monthly payment <m>M</m> that we need to make to pay off the loan is given by the formula
        <md>
          M(r,t) = \frac{1500r}{1-\frac{1}{\left(1+\frac{r}{12}\right)^{12t}}}.
        </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the monthly payments on this loan if the interest rate is 6% and the duration of the loan is 5 years.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          $<m>347.99</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.06,5) = \frac{1500(0.06)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.06}{12})^{12(5)}}} = \$347.99</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Create a table of values that illustrates the trace of <m>M</m> with <m>r</m> fixed at 5%. Use yearly values of <m>t</m> from 2 to 6. Round payments to the nearest penny. Explain in detail in words what this trace tells us about <m>M</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,2) = \$789.69</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,3) = \$539.48</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,4) = \$414.53</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,5) = \$339.68</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,6) = \$289.89</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          These traces indicates that for a loan with an interest rate of <m>5</m>%, the monthly payment decreases as the duration of the loan increases.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,2) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(2)}}} = \$789.69</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,3) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(3)}}} = \$539.48</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,4) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(4)}}} = \$414.53</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,5) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(5)}}} = \$339.68</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,6) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(6)}}} = \$289.89</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Create a table of values that illustrates the trace of <m>M</m> with <m>t</m> fixed at 3 years. Use rates from 3% to 11% in increments of 2%. Round payments to the nearest penny. Explain in detail what this trace tells us about <m>M</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.03,3) = \$523.46</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,3) = \$539.48</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.07,3) = \$555.79</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.09,3) = \$572.40</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.11,3) = \$589.30</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          These traces indicates that for a loan with a duration of 3 years, the monthly payment increases as the interest rate increases.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.03,3) = \frac{1500(0.03)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.03}{12})^{12(2)}}} = \$523.46</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.05,3) = \frac{1500(0.05)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.05}{12})^{12(3)}}} = \$539.48</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.07,3) = \frac{1500(0.07)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.07}{12})^{12(4)}}} = \$555.79</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.09,3) = \frac{1500(0.09)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.09}{12})^{12(5)}}} = \$572.40</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>M(0.11,3) = \frac{1500(0.11)}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{0.11}{12})^{12(6)}}} = \$589.30</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the combinations of interest rates and durations of loans that result in a monthly payment of $200. Solve the equation <m>M(r,t) = 200</m> for <m>t</m> to write the duration of the loan in terms of the interest rate. Graph this level curve and explain as best you can the relationship between <m>t</m> and <m>r</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>t = \frac{ln(\frac{1}{1 - \frac{15r}{2}})}{12ln(1 + \frac{r}{12})}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          This level curve indicates that as the loan interest rate increases, the loan duration for a $<m>200</m> monthly loan payment increases at an increasing rate.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>200 = \frac{1500r}{1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>200(1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}}) = 1500r</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>(1 - \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}}) = \frac{1500r}{200}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>- \frac{1}{(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}} = \frac{15r}{2} -1</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{1}{(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}} = 1 - \frac{15r}{2}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>1 = (1- \frac{15r}{2}) * (1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>(1 + \frac{r}{12})^{12t} = \frac{1}{1- \frac{15r}{2}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>12t*ln(1 + \frac{r}{12}) = ln(\frac{1}{1- \frac{15r}{2}})</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>t = \frac{ln(\frac{1}{1- \frac{15r}{2}})}{12*ln(1 + \frac{r}{12})}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
</exercise>
  
  <exercise xml:id="Ez-9-1-3">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the function <m>h</m> defined by <m>h(x,y) = 8 - \sqrt{4 - x^2 - y^2}</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the domain of <m>h</m>?  (Hint:  describe a set of ordered pairs in the plane by explaining their relationship relative to a key circle.)
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x^{2} + y^{2} \leq 4</m> This is the set of all ordered pairs on, or inside, a circle with radius of 2, centered at (0,0)
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We cannot have a negative value under the square root. Therefore <m>4 - \left( x^{2} + y^{2} \right) \geq 0</m>, so <m>x^{2} + y^{2} \leq 4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <em>range</em> of a function is the set of all outputs the function generates.  Given that the range of the square root function <m>g(t) = \sqrt{t}</m> is the set of all nonnegative real numbers, what do you think is the range of <m>h</m>?  Why?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>6 \leq h(x,y) \leq 8</m>. The value of the square root expression is <m>0 \leq 2</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The maximum value of the square root is equal to 2 when <m>x=0, y=0</m>. The minimum value of the square root is 0. Subtract these values from 8 to a range of <m>6 \leq h(x,y) \leq 8</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose 4 different values from the range of <m>h</m> and plot the corresponding level curves in the plane.  What is the shape of a typical level curve?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          A typical level curve is a circle centered at <m>(0,0)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Subtract 8 from both sides to get <m>h - 8 = - \sqrt{4 - x^2 - y^2}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Divide by -1 to get <m>8 - h = \sqrt{4 - x^2 - y^2}</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Square both side to get <m>(8-h)^2 = 4 -x^2 -y^2</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Then <m>x^2 + y^2 = 4 - (8-h)^2</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the formula for a circle centered at <m>(0,0)</m> with a radius of <m>\sqrt{4 - (8-h)^2}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose 5 different values of <m>x</m> (including at least one negative value and zero), and sketch the corresponding traces of the function <m>h</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          A typical trace is the bottom half of an ellipse.   
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It follow from part d that if <m>x^2 + y^2 = 4 - (8-h)^2</m>, then <m>x^2 = 4 - (8-h)^2 - y^2</m> and <m>x = - \sqrt{4 - (8-h)^2 - x^2}</m>. Then choose y values to graph the traces.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose 5 different values of <m>y</m> (including at least one negative value and zero), and sketch the corresponding traces of the function <m>h</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          A typical trace is the bottom half of an ellipse.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It follows from e that <m>y = - \sqrt{4 - (8-h)^2 - x^2}</m>. Then choose x values to graph the traces.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Sketch an overall picture of the surface generated by <m>h</m> and write at least one sentence to describe how the surface appears visually.  Does the surface remind you of a familiar physical structure in nature?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The surface is a bowl opening up with a vertex <m>(0,0,6)</m> with a maximum height of 8.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The surface is a bowl opening up with a vertex <m>(0,0,6)</m> with a maximum height of 8.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  


  

